@ENDNODE

@NODE "Installation" "Installation"
@TOC "Main"
Just copy WBAttack anywhere you like. I suggest you to copy it either to
"SYS:c" or "SYS:utilities".

WBAttack is (mainly) intended to be used with programs like Toolmanager
which allow you to start a program by pressing a configurable hotkey.
The only thing you probably have to know is that WBAttack must be started
as CLI-Program and 4096 Bytes of Stack should be enough. Have a look at
@{" Usage " LINK "Usage"} to see the possible arguments. Most probably you will use WBAttack 
with the SWITCH option:

			      WBAttack SWITCH
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage" "Usage"
@TOC "Main"
WBAttack can only be used from a CLI/Shell (or started as a CLI/Shell pro-
gram). It has the following argument template:

	      @{FG SHINE}DOBACKDROP=ON/S,NOBACKDROP=OFF/S,SWITCH/S@{FG TEXT}

@{FG SHINE}DOBACKDROP@{FG TEXT}: Makes the main Workbench window be a backdrop window (if it
            isn't already)
            
@{FG SHINE}NOBACKDROP@{FG TEXT}: Makes the main Workbench window be a standard window (if it
	    isn't already)

@{FG SHINE}SWITCH    @{FG TEXT}: Changes the backdrop mode of the main Workbench window. If the
	    window was backdrop it will become normal, if it was normal it
	    will become backdrop.


